Daemon troubleshooting.

A small set of commands answers most what-is-wrong-with-docker questions. The daemon's reported configuration shows all its current settings. The version command tells you quickly whether the daemon is even up. The disk-usage command gives you a breakdown of what is consuming space, with a verbose form for per-image and per-container detail. There is a live event stream of everything the daemon sees, and the prune family of commands cleans up stopped containers, unused images, networks, and, with care, volumes.

When the daemon will not start at all, you check its service status, read the last couple of hundred lines of its log through the system journal, or run it in the foreground with debug logging to watch it fail in real time. The common causes are a handful. A broken configuration file, a syntax error or unknown key, which the daemon can validate for you. A storage-driver mismatch, where the data directory was created by one driver and you reconfigured to another. A port already in use by another process. Or wrong ownership on the data directory after a botched move.

When the daemon is up but misbehaving, the same tools narrow it down. If it is slow, you check whether the data directory is on a tiny or saturated disk and whether disk input-output is maxed out. If the disk is filling, the disk-usage command tells you how bad it is, measuring the data subdirectories shows which is fattest, and an aggressive prune is often exactly the right call. The pattern throughout is the same, look at the daemon's own reports first, then the system journal, then the disk, and the cause usually surfaces quickly.
